@node "Introduction" "Introduction..."
@next "Requirements"
                            @{b}Introduction@{ub}

    This is an Amiga port of Sangband 0.9.5, yet another variant of Angband.

    Sangband [Skills Angband] allocates experiences to skills, rather than
have the concept of character level. So while killing monsters gains you
experience (as normal), it's up to you how you invest that experience; you
may choose to increase your endurance, or weapon skills, etc.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements..."
@next "Installation"
                            @{b}Requirements@{ub}

@{b}Absolute Minimum@{ub}

You'll need at *least* this to run plain Angband.

Kickstart 1.3
1.5 Mb of memory
68000 - a faster processor is nice, but by no means necessary.

@{b}Recommended Level@{ub}

This is what I'd recommend to get the most out of SAngband:

Kickstart 3.0 or better
2Mb of memory
68020 or better.
A Hard drive.

Note that usage under 1.3 is somewhat restricted. As from this point, extra
1.3 code is pretty unlikely to happen; I'm going to assume that everyone
has 2.04 or better. The game will still run under 1.3, but you won't be able
to use many of the advanced features.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installing Angband"
@next "Differences"
                            @{b}Installing Angband@{ub}

Installing Angband is straightforward. I`ve not provided an Installer script
because it doesn't need one.

   Installing to Hard disc:

      Just unpack the archive to a directory of your choice.

      If you have a KS 2.0 or better system that's all you'll need to do. To
      run SAngband, just run the program 'bin/SAngband'



      If you only have Kickstart 1.3, you'll also need to:

      Place these two commands in your 'S:startup-sequence', or, better, make
       a small script file with these two lines in and execute that everytime
       you want to start Angband:

      assign SAngband: DH1:Games/Angband
      path add SAngband:bin

      Replace 'DH1:Games/SAngband' with your path. Note that 'SAngband:'
      needs to point to the directory containing 'file', 'data', 'apex' etc.

   3.2. Floppy installation

      You can (just about) install 'SAngband' onto floppy discs, but it's
      pretty tight. Compression utils might help.

      First get two empty (and formatted) discs. Name the first one
      'SAngband', and call the second 'AMain' (or something). Assuming
      you've extracted the archive somewhere (RAM: ??), copy the 'bin'
      directory to 'AMain'. Everything else ought to go on the 'SAngband:'
      disc.

      You (probably) won't be able to fit everything on the second disc
      I suggest you delete the sound files, and/or the help files. And the
      graphics if you don't use them.

      I`m guessing everyone still using an Amiga has a hard drive these days.
      You cam mail me if you`re having trouble running from floppies.

                            @{b}Playing Angband@{ub}

   Assuming you have Angband installed properly, just run the 'bin/SAngband'
   file. Note you can use the '-u' option to load a previous savefile; if
   you don't specify one, SAngband will attempt to load the one you last
   used.

   SAngband -uMark         (or whatever your savefile is called)

   Type SAngband -? for a list of options.

   Note AngMan now has some (very basic) save file handling. As always,
   its being worked on.

@endnode

