@node "node004" "Graphics"
@node "node005"
                           @{b}Graphics@{ub}

   Standard Angband is designed to be played on an 80 x 24 terminal using
ASCII graphics. If you want to play Angband in this mode, just turn
graphics off using AngMan and it'll use a 16 colour screen.

   With graphics on, Angband will attempt to use a 640 x 200 x 32 colour
screen. This is the minimum screen setup needed to use graphics.

   You can also use higher resolutions if you like (under 'Screen Prefs' in
AngMan), but at the moment you can't choose the number of colours. Note
Angband won't actually utilise the increased resolution - it still sticks to
that 80 x 24 screen. What you *can* do is activate some of the extra windows
(see @{"Windows" link "node006" 0}). For example, one window could contain an inventory listing,
one a character dump, etc.

   To increase the available screen space, you can:

a) Use a bigger screen :)
b) Pick a larger overscan setting in AngMan.
c) We PAL users can use the bottom ~60 lines.

   Please note that graphics cards aren't supported particularly well at the
moment. It should now work (previous versions of Angband may not have worked
at all), but it needs *major* improvement, especially the graphics remapping.

	To use graphics, turn the `RTG` option on in AngMan or add `SCREEN.rtg`
to the settings.prf file.

   Also note that it doesn`t attempt to autodetect graphics cards at the
moment, though it will do soon. I`m not totally sure how to do this...
anyone know if GetBitMapAttr(...) and testing for the IS_FOREIGN flag
will always work?

                        @{b}Other graphics options@{ub}

Angband can also be played on a public screen (under KS2.0 or better). Note
that 2.0/1 public screen support is very dodgy at the moment.

[2.0/2.1 don't have the ObtainBestPen() call, so the colours under <3.0
will probably be totally wrong. Try using 'Load Palette', or redefining the
palette (either with the 'Redefine Colours' option or some other utility)

I'll improve this in future versions.

Of course, you can use custom screens as normal]

Under 3.0, public screens should work without problems. Turn on
'Use public screen' in AngMan/Screen Prefs, and supply the name of the
desired public screen in the string gadget below. So now you can play
Angband on your Workbench.

                            @{b}Quick Gfx@{ub}

The 'Quick Gfx' option attempts to speed up graphic redraws on custom
screens. It only works on screens with 8x8 fonts and 8x8 icons. Generally,
the graphics will redraw at least twice as quickly with this turned on
(and often faster).

Don't use this option unless you feel you need to - as it writes directly
to screen memory it's rather unsafe :)

Having said that, I've never had any problems.

***************************** IMPORTANT ***********************

Oh, and don't use this if you have a graphics card (like you would, eh?).
It just won't work, and might crash your machine.

                        @{b}Other gfx options@{ub}

You can redefine the colours using the 'Redefine Colours' menu option.
This brings up a ReqTools palette requester.

Note this won't actually save the new palette unless you choose
'Save Palette' from the menu (RAMIGA + 's'). This saves the colours to
the 'user/colours.prf' file, which is automatically loaded upon startup.

There is a 'Load Palette' option (RAMIGA + 'l').

You can have graphics in store/equipment/inventory listings - see the
'Options/User Interface' menu.

There are Intuition Menus, which again can be controlled by AngMan. This
requires KS 2.0 or better.

And finally, you can also pick any monospace font for the display; see @{"Windows" link "node006" 0}

@endnode

@node "node005" "Sounds"
@node "node006"
                                @{b}Sound@{ub}

Angband is supplied with sound effects for things like attacking, eating,
dying etc.

These are stored in the 'xtra/sound' directory (as 8SVX files). You can
replace these with more interesting sounds (which must be in 8SVX format).
To stop certain sounds being played, just move them out of the directory.

@endnode

@node "node006" "Windows"

                                @{b}Windows@{ub}

   Angband can have upto seven additional windows, which can be used to
display inventory listings, messages, character dumps etc.

   Previous versions of Amiga Angband required a public screen for this
feature, but now you can use these windows on a normal custom screen.

   This section assumes you use AngMan.

   To turn on a window, run AngMan and pick 'Define Windows'. The cyclic
gadget at the top lets you choose a term window.

   From the top, we have:

'Use' - select this to activate a window. Note that the 'Main' window
*must* be activated.

'X Pos' - The left part of the window, in pixels
'Y Pos' - The top part of the window, in pixels
'Cols'  - The width of the window, in *characters*. Note that you have to
          allow for the width of the window borders when setting this.
          Normally, you can't fit 80 characters on a 640 pixel screen.
          This isn't normally a problem (see below).
'Rows'  - The height of the window, in characters.

The bottom two gadgets set the window name, and the font you'd like to use.

The lowest gadget, `Use scrolling`, allows you to have scroll bars in
the window. Normally, this should be *off*; this option is rather hacky.

If you want to use a window in Angband, make sure 'Use' is selected. Then
save and run Angband. If the window does not appear, go to the 'Windows'
menu, and select the relevant window - it should now be created.

Now you should (hopefully) have a new window on screen. You can drag this
around and resize it as you wish, but note that after you've resized a window
its dimensions may be adjusted slightly.

Once you're happy with the window setup, choose 'Save Windows' from the
'Windows' menu. When you next load Angband the windows ought to remain where
you left them.

@endnode

