@node "Extra" "Extra - AngMan"

                              @{b}Extra@{ub}

   New for this version of Angband is the 'AngMan' program (also in the
'bin' directory). This is a small (but hopefully useful) GUI that allows
you to experiment with different options without messing around with
text editors and a copy of the source code.

It uses the 'Triton' GUI library, available from Aminet.

I apologise for the lack of proper documentation, but I'm hoping it's
fairly intuitive.

AngMUI is currently in progress, which will be much nicer, and will
probably replace AngMan.

@{"Requirements" link "node001" 0}
@{"Operation" link "node002" 0}

@endnode

@node "node001" "Requirements"

                              @{b}Requirements@{ub}

AngMan, unlike the main Angband executable, requires Kickstart 2.1 or
better. It also needs the 'triton.library' somewhere in your 'LIBS:'
path. The 2.1 requirement is from AngMan, not Triton - it ought to become
2.0 compatible eventually.

It also needs a Sangband: path assigment.

@endnode

@node "node002" "Operation"

                              @{b}Operation@{ub}

AngMan still recognises only one argument, and doesn`t know about tooltypes
at all. Sigh.

You can supply a `PATH` argument:

   eg. AngMan path xh2:source/other/angband/zangband206

@endnode

@node "node008" "Known Bugs & FAQ"

                            @{b}Known Bugs & FAQ@{ub}

Here is a list of some of the problems I know about. Most of these should
hopefully get fixed.

  *  Graphics card behaviour is very nasty. In future versions I may
     support graphics cards directly with Picasso 96/insert similar. Note
     (I think) this only really applies if you use the graphics (not text)

  *  Graphics in inventory/equip/store options will not work properly with
     RTG mode on. This probably won`t get fixed until I get a graphics card
     myself.

  *  2.0/2.1 public screen support very flaky. Apparently it
     doesn`t work at all, though I can`t figure out why.

  *  Quick graphics option should optimise text too.

  *  Scroll bars are a little dodgy at the moment.

And now, the mini-faq:
                                  @{b}AngMan@{ub}

Q: AngMan refuses to load at all, or crashes.
A: Make sure that an appropriate version of triton.library is in LIBS:
   I've heard that the 3.0 version of library crashes on 2.0, rather than
   gracefully aborting; hopefully this is wrong. Some early versions of Triton
   also ask for key files and refuse to load without them - try a more modern
   version.

Q: AngMan won't load the settings.prf file!
A: First, make sure you actually have a settings.prf file in your user
   directory; AngMan won't create one for you.

   Assuming you've left AngMan in 'bin/', it will look in the 'user/'
   directory first, then look in 'Angband:user/'. So try assigning Angband:
   to the appropriate place, and run AngMan again.

   You can also supply AngMan with a path, using the path keyword:

   eg. AngMan path xh2:source/other/angband/zangband210

Q: AngMan is eating up all my CPU time :((
A: This bug should now be fixed.

                                  @{b}Angband@{ub}

Q: How do you persuade Angband to use a public screen?
A: The easiest way is to use AngMan:

    Go into 'Screen Prefs', and ensure 'Use Public screen' is checked.
    Put the public screen name into the 'Public screen' gadget below.
    (For the Workbench screen, use 'Workbench')

    If you don't like AngMan, or can't run it, you can edit the settings.prf
    file directly:

    Load settings.prf into your favourite text editor, and delete (or
    comment out) all references to SCREEN.mode
    Now insert a line 'SCREEN.name <name of public screen>'

Q: The screen looks odd...
A: Angband tries, by default, to use a NTSC screen. So if you have a NTSC
   monitor driver present it may produce some interesting results. To fix,
   either a) choose a screenmode b) resize the main window to fill the screen
   c) remove the NTSC driver.

Q: The colours look odd in graphics mode.
A: If you find that the colours look wrong, try using a 32 colour screen if
   you can. If that doesn't work, try temporarily removing the file
   colours.prf in the 'user' directory.

@endnode

@node "links" "Links"

                                  @{b}Links@{ub}

For more information about Angband, you can visit one of these:

ftp://export.andrew.cmu.edu/angband

   The Official Angband FTP site. Angband will be found in the 'Amiga'
directory but most Amiga stuff will be found in the Variant or Incoming
areas. Note that Incoming is not publicly viewable; you can only retrieve
files if you know the exact name. Amiga archives are generally of the
form ???amxxx.lha, where ??? indicates the variant (zng,sng etc.) and
xxx is the version. There are also a couple of LZX archives floating around,
because I can't make up my mind which format is best :)

http://www.phial.com/angband                      - Official Angband Site

   This has an extensive bug list, some information on Angband's history, etc.
It also has a small links section and pointers to the FAQ and ftp site. It's
aimed more at developers than users though, and isn't updated all that
frequently.

http://homepages.enterprise.net/bablos/angband    - Angband Variants Page

   Contains a list of all known (and some unknown) variants, as well as
descriptions, mail addresses, pointers to the source and executables etc.
If you suddenly need to know what Ying-Yang Angband is, or what version
of Zangband we're up to, visit this. It's somewhat Amiga orientated but
covers everything. It also has a huge list of Angband links, and even
some information on Nethack, ADOM, etc. Highly recommended.

http://www2.krisalis.co.uk/wwwdheb/index.html     - Roguelike News Page

   Useful and updated most weekdays, this holds most of the important
roguelike news. Also has articles on rl development, links, etc. Another
good one.

rec.games.roguelike.angband                       - The newsgroup.

rec.games.roguelike.development                   - Development newsgroup.

   For discussing the development of rl games in general, not just Angband.
Too much discussion of OOP for my liking, but still...

@endnode

@node "future" "What's next?"

                                  @{b}What's next@{ub}

Okay - here are the things that I'm planning, in order of likely arrival.

If you've got *any* ideas, even a small suggestion, please let me know.

 256 colour tile support. There are a set of 16x16, 256 colour tiles by Adam
  Bolt that look amazing but they need fairly extensive changes to the
  Angband code. From the feedback I've had most Angband/Zangband players
  use ASCII anyway - but I don't. I've not touched this for a while, since
  I've heard that the maintainer of Angband is looking into it.

 Better graphics card support. I'm hoping to get a BlizzardVision PPC card
  pretty soon which should give me some incentive to improve it :)

 'Fancy' lighting effects in graphics mode.

 More of an 'Amiga' feel - eg. tooltypes, icons, etc.

 Better documentation. I've been saying this for months though.

 AngMUI, which is currently about 45% finished.

@endnode


